[[Image:House of wonders inside zanzibar.jpg|thumb|right|''Shungwaya'': an inexact replica mtepe<ref name="ib"/> built in 2003 and displayed at the [[House of Wonders]] Museum in [[Stone Town]], [[Zanzibar]].]] The '''mtepe''' is a boat associated with the [[Swahili people]] (the word "boat" in the [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] [[Swahili language]] being ''mtepe''). The mtepe's planks are held together by wooden pegs<ref>A.H.J. Prins. "Uncertainties in Coastal Cultural History: The Ngalawa and the Mtepe” ''Tanganyika Notes and Records'' No.55: pp.204-214</ref> and [[coir]]<ref name="rma"/>{{efn|ie. coconut fibers}}, so it is a [[sewn boat]] designed to be flexible<ref name="rma"/>{{efn|They are in this manner similar to traditional lashed Polynesian craft, whose flexible construction techniques have in part been carried forward to modern cruising designs and championed by [[James Wharram]].<ref>Harvey, Derek, ''Multihulls for Cruising and Racing'', Adlard Coles, London 1990 p. 16, {{ISBN|0-7136-6414-2}}</ref>}} in contrast to the rigid vessels of western technique.
==Extinction== [[File:Mtepe on the beach at Zanzibar (about 1890).png|thumb|''mtepe'' on the beach at Zanzibar, circa 1890.]] The cessation of the production of ''mtepe'' has been ascribed to the arrival of the Portuguese in the Indian Ocean in the 15th century, leading to boat builders adopting alternative, western shipbuilding techniques.<ref name="rma">Robert Marshall Adams B.A.S. ''Construction and Qualitative Analysis of a Sewn Boat of the Western Indian Ocean''. University of Minnesota, 1985.</ref>
==Preservation== Nearly a dozen photographs and nine known model ''mtepe'' have been preserved.<ref name="rma"/> Three models are kept at the [[Fort Jesus Museum]], a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] fort built in 1591 located on [[Mombasa Island]], [[Kenya]].<ref name="rma"/> One model is kept at the [[Lamu Museum]], {{Convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} north.<ref name="rma"/> One model is kept at the [[National Maritime Museum]], [[Greenwich]], [[London]].<ref name="ib">{{cite web|url=http://indigenousboats.blogspot.fr/2012/09/the-mtepes-of-kenya.html|title=The Mtepes of Kenya|year=2012|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> One model is kept at the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]], [[Kensington]], [[London]].<ref name="ib"/>
